                <exercise workspace="1in">
                    <title>Preview Activity 4.2.1</title>
                    <introduction>
        <p> Let's begin by reviewing some important ideas that we have
        seen previously.</p>
      </introduction>

      <task >
        <statement>
	  <p> Suppose that <m>A</m> is a square matrix and that
	  the nonzero vector <m>\xvec</m> is a solution to
	  the homogeneous equation <m>A\xvec = \zerovec</m>.  What can
	  we conclude about the invertibility of <m>A</m>?  </p>
        </statement>
        
        <solution>
	  <p> The matrix cannot have a pivot position in every
	  column so it is not invertible. </p>
        </solution>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
	  <p> How does the determinant <m>\det(A)</m> tell us if
	  there is a nonzero solution to the homogeneous equation
	  <m>A\xvec = \zerovec</m>? </p>
        </statement>
       
        <solution>
	  <p> If there is a nonzero solution to the homogeneous
	  equation <m>A\xvec=\zerovec</m>, then <m>A</m> is not
	  invertible so <m>\det(A) = 0</m>. </p>
        </solution>
      </task>

      <task >
        <statement>
	  <p> Suppose that
	  <me>
	    A = \left[\begin{array}{rrr}
	    3 \amp -1 \amp 1 \\
	    0 \amp 2 \amp 4 \\
	    1 \amp 1 \amp 3 \\
	    \end{array}\right]
	    </me>.
	    Find the determinant <m>\det(A)</m>.  What does this tell us
	    about the solution space to the homogeneous equation <m>A\xvec
	  = \zerovec</m>? </p>
        </statement>
       
        <solution>
	  <p> We find that <m>\det(A) = 0</m> so there is a nonzero
	  solution to the homogeneous equation. </p>
        </solution>
      </task>

      <task >
        <statement>
	  <p> Find a basis for <m>\nul(A)</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        
        <solution>
	  <p> The reduced row echelon form of <m>A</m> is
	  <me>
	    \left[\begin{array}{rrr}
	    1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
	    0 \amp 1 \amp 2 \\
	    0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
	    \end{array}\right]
	  </me>
	  so the solution space to the homogeneous equation may be
	  described parametrically as
	  <m>x=x_3\threevec{-1}{-2}{1}</m>.  A basis for
	  <m>\nul(A)</m> is therefore
	  <m>\threevec{-1}{-2}{1}</m>. </p>
        </solution>
      </task>

      <task >
        <statement>
	  <p> What is the relationship between the rank of a matrix
	  and the dimension of its null space? </p>
        </statement>
        
        <solution>
	  <p> If <m>A</m> is an <m>n\times n</m>
	  matrix, then <m>\dim~\nul(A) = n-\text{rank}(A)</m>. </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
                    
                    
                </exercise>

            </page>

            <page>
                <exercise workspace="5in">
                    <title>Finding Eigenvalues</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            If <m>\vvec \neq \zerovec</m> is an eigenvector, then there is a scalar <m>\lambda</m> 
                            such that 
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <m>A\vvec = \lambda \vvec</m>. We can rearrange this equation to see that this implies
                            <me>
                                (A-\lambda I)\vvec = \zerovec
                            </me>
                        Since we know <m>(A-\lambda I)</m> is not invertible (since <m>\vvec</m> is a non-zero solution), we know
                        <m>\text{det}(A-\lambda I) =0 </m>. This gives us a relationship in which to solve for <m>\lambda</m>.
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="5in">
                    <title>Example: Finding Eigenvalues</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let 
                            <me>
	  A_1 = \left[\begin{array}{rr}
	  1 \amp 2 \\
	  2 \amp 1 \\
	  \end{array}\right], \,\,\,\,

      A_2 = \left[\begin{array}{rr}
	0 \amp -1 \\
	1 \amp 0 \\
	\end{array}\right], \,\,\,\,

    A_3 = \left[\begin{array}{rrr}
	  3 \amp -1 \amp 4 \\
	  0 \amp -2 \amp 3 \\
	  0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
	  \end{array}\right]
	</me>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            For <m>A_1</m>, the characteristic polynomial is <m>\lambda^2 - 2\lambda - 3= (\lambda-3)(\lambda+1) =
		0</m> so we find eigenvalues <m>\lambda = 3</m> and
		<m>\lambda = -1</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>\det(A_2-\lambda I) = \lambda^2 + 1 = 0</m> so there
		are complex eigenvalues, <m>\lambda = i</m> and
		<m>\lambda = -i</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Because the determinant of a triangular matrix equals
		the product of its diagonal entries, 
		the eigenvalues of <m>A_3</m> are equal to the entries on the
		diagonal.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace="3in">
                    <title>Finding Eigenvectors</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Eigenvectors are solutions to
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <m>(A - \lambda I)\vvec = \zerovec</m>. That is, the <term>Eigenspace of A associated to <m>\lambda</m></term> is
                            <me>
                                E_\lambda := \text{Nul}(A - \lambda I)
                            </me>
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="6in">
                    <title>Example: Finding Eigenvectors</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            If <m>A= \left[\begin{array}{rr}
	  1 \amp 2 \\
	  2 \amp 1 \\
	  \end{array}\right]</m>, then <m>\lambda = -1, 3</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p> We have
	  <me>
	    A - 3I =
	    \mattwo{-2}{2}{2}{-2}
	    \sim
	    \mattwo{1}{-1}{0}{0}\text{.}
	  </me>
	  The null space <m>\nul(A-3I)</m> is one-dimensional with
	  basis <m>\twovec{1}{1}</m>.
	  </p>

      <p> We have
	  <me>
	    A - (-1)I =
	    \mattwo{2}{2}{2}{2}
	    \sim
	    \mattwo{1}{1}{0}{0}\text{.}
	  </me>
	  The null space <m>\nul(A+I)</m> is one-dimensional with
	  basis <m>\twovec{-1}{1}</m>.
	  </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
